      Liebor
   =20
 =20
The way that global financial markets worked for decades is that trillions =
of dollars of floating-rate loans and interest-rate derivatives were indexe=
d to Libor, the London interbank offered rate. And the way Libor worked was=
 that someone =E2=80=94=C2=A0at the time relevant to our story=C2=A0it was =
the British Bankers=E2=80=99 Association[1] =E2=80=94=C2=A0would call up a =
group of big international banks and ask them =E2=80=9Chow much would you h=
ave to pay right now to borrow dollars for one month,=E2=80=9D and they=E2=
=80=99d answer, and the BBA would take some trimmed average of their answer=
s, and that was one-month dollar Libor. And there were other Libors for oth=
er currencies and tenors, computed in the same way.Most important financial=
 benchmarks do not work this way. The S&P 500 index is not calculated by ca=
lling some banks and saying =E2=80=9Chey how=C2=A0much would you pay for th=
ese 500 stocks=E2=80=9D and averaging their answers. The S&P 500 index is c=
alculated based on the last trade of each stock on a public stock exchange.=
 Most indexes are based on actual trades.[2] But Libor was invented because=
 it was  very useful, for the floating-rate loan business, to have an index=
 of=C2=A0banks=E2=80=99 unsecured borrowing costs, and unsecured short-term=
 bank debt did not really trade on a transparent public exchange. It traded=
=C2=A0in an informal, telephone-based interbank market, and the easiest way=
 to find out what trades banks were doing was to call them.Also, though, th=
ey didn=E2=80=99t do trades in every Libor tenor and currency every day. If=
 you wanted to know how much a bank would pay to borrow Danish kroner for t=
wo months =E2=80=94=C2=A0which was a real Libor rate =E2=80=94 you could no=
t compute that every day based on how much each Libor bank actually paid to=
 borrow kroner for two months that day. Big international banks did not bor=
row kroner for two months every day.=C2=A0Certainly not every day at exactl=
y the time the BBA called them to ask. But a bank which had borrowed kroner=
 for one month an hour ago, and borrowed dollars for three months five minu=
tes ago, and had a general sense of the curve of its various short-term bor=
rowing costs, could probably give you a good guess at how much it would hav=
e to pay to borrow kroner for two months right now. So you could just call =
it and ask it for that guess. Libor was =E2=80=9Cthe rate at which banks do=
n't lend to each other,=E2=80=9D people said.The problem is that Libor also=
 became the rate underpinning trillions of dollars of derivatives contracts=
, and the banks traded those derivatives and built up large positions. And =
some days it would be good for the derivatives traders to have a low Libor =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0they had to pay Libor on a bunch of contracts resetting that=
 day, so a low Libor would let them pay less =E2=80=94=C2=A0and other days =
it would be good for the derivatives traders to have a high Libor. And the =
derivatives traders realized that, if it was worth $1,000,000 to their bank=
 to have Libor be one basis point lower, then it was worth $200,000 to thei=
r bonus to have Libor be one basis point lower, which meant that it was wor=
th calling up their bank=E2=80=99s Libor submitter =E2=80=94=C2=A0the perso=
n who answered the phone when the BBA called =E2=80=94=C2=A0and saying =E2=
=80=9Chey mate I=E2=80=99ll buy you a case of Champagne if you submit a low=
er Libor.=E2=80=9D And then the BBA would call the submitter and say =E2=80=
=9Cwhere can you borrow yen for three months,=E2=80=9D and the submitter wo=
uld say =E2=80=9Coh 0.525=E2=80=9D when in his heart of hearts he knew=C2=
=A0that the real answer was 0.545, and the BBA would average that in, and 3=
-month yen Libor would be a smidge=C2=A0lower than it would otherwise have =
been, and the bank would make money on the derivatives, and the derivatives=
 traders would get their bonuses and the submitter would get his Champagne.=
This went on for a while and eventually regulators and prosecutors noticed =
it and it became a huge huge huge scandal[3] and:=09Banks were fined  billi=
ons and  billions of dollars for rigging Libor;=09Bank regulators decided=
=C2=A0to  get rid of Libor and replace it with other rates that are harder =
to rig; and=09Various derivatives traders were arrested and prosecuted for =
rigging Libor.Point 1 is sort of self-explanatory. In the post-crisis perio=
d, if banks do shady stuff and get caught, they pay big fines. Point 2 is q=
uite complicated, because the issues we discussed above =E2=80=94=C2=A0that=
 banks do not actually borrow unsecured in every tenor and currency every d=
ay, that the bank funding market is not very transparent, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0remain true. The way regulators in the U.S. have addressed these issues =
is to replace Libor with a benchmark interest=C2=A0rate called=C2=A0SOFR, t=
he Secured Overnight Financing Rate,=C2=A0which reflects the cost of borrow=
ing money for one day secured by Treasury securities. That rate can be calc=
ulated based on actual transactions in a liquid market. I should say, regul=
ators are in the slow process of replacing Libor with SOFR; I am talking ab=
out Libor in the past tense but that is a bit misleading and it is still in=
 wide use despite being phased out. This is partly for reasons of inertia, =
but also because using an overnight secured rate=C2=A0raises its own issues=
 for floating-rate lending, etc., which we have talked  about  before but w=
ill not talk about again here.Here we will talk about Point 3. Some bank tr=
aders were prosecuted for rigging Libor.[4] In the U.S., they were prosecut=
ed for =E2=80=9Cwire fraud,=E2=80=9D the crime of lying to people to make m=
oney.[5]There is something a little bit odd about this, if you think about =
it too hard. The BBA would call up a bank=E2=80=99s Libor submitter and say=
 =E2=80=9Cwhere could you borrow yen=C2=A0for three months=E2=80=9D and the=
 submitter would say =E2=80=9C0.525=E2=80=9D when the correct answer was 0.=
545. But what does it mean to say that the correct answer was 0.545? It doe=
s=C2=A0not=C2=A0mean that, as the submitter was saying =E2=80=9C0.525,=E2=
=80=9D he was simultaneously entering into a three-month unsecured borrowin=
g agreement to borrow dollars at 0.545%. It means that the submitter=E2=80=
=99s unbiased best guess about what the bank would pay, right that minute, =
to borrow a reasonable amount of dollars for three months, was 0.545%, but =
he said 0.525% due to impure motives.But of course the submitter=E2=80=99s =
unbiased best guess was just a guess about a hypothetical question, and for=
 most Libor tenors and currencies on most days that guess would not line up=
 precisely with a contemporaneous actual transaction. And so you could not =
prove that that best guess =E2=80=94=C2=A00.545% here =E2=80=94=C2=A0was =
=E2=80=9Ccorrect,=E2=80=9D that it reflected the true answer to the BBA=E2=
=80=99s question, which was to submit =E2=80=9Cthe rate at which [the bank]=
=C2=A0could borrow funds, were it to do so by asking for=C2=A0and then acce=
pting inter-bank offers in reasonable market size just prior to [11 a.m. Lo=
ndon time].=E2=80=9D[6]Which means that you=C2=A0also could not prove that =
the biased, dishonest, Champagne-induced guess =E2=80=94=C2=A00.525% here =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0was=C2=A0false. Could the bank have borrowed yen for three m=
