tions,=C2=A0pointing out that=C2=A0there was no proof that the numbers they=
 submitted were wrong. And last week the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Seco=
nd Circuit agreed with them and  tossed out their convictions. Maybe the nu=
mbers were right! Who can say? The numbers were necessarily subjective, and=
 anyway the prosecutors forgot to prove they were wrong.Here is the Second =
Circuit=E2=80=99s opinion. Connolly and Black traded interest-rate derivati=
ves and cash products, and were accused of=C2=A0pressuring Deutsche Bank=E2=
=80=99s Libor submitters to submit wrong Libors. Two Deutsche Bank Libor su=
bmitters cooperated with the government and testified against them. These w=
ere James King and Michael Curtler, who worked on a cash money market tradi=
ng desk, =E2=80=9Cborrowing money in the interbank=C2=A0market in order to =
fund DB's cash needs.=E2=80=9DThe way the cash desk worked is that it would=
 borrow money in the interbank market and then lend it to other Deutsche Ba=
nk units to fund their operations;=C2=A0the cash desk would show a real, li=
ve, market-based price to those other units.=C2=A0King and Curtler had litt=
le spreadsheets (called =E2=80=9Cpricers=E2=80=9D)=C2=A0that they used to d=
ecide what that price would be, and they would use that price =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the price that=C2=A0they=C2=A0charged Deutsche Bank=E2=80=99s other unit=
s =E2=80=94=C2=A0as the basis for their Libor submission. Though sometimes =
they=E2=80=99d bump it up or down a bit based on their market judgment. Fro=
m the opinion (citations omitted):In addition to the above alterations in t=
he pricer, King each day=C2=A0consulted, inter alia, five interbank cash br=
okers before settling on DB's LIBOR=C2=A0submissions.=C2=A0He testified tha=
t it was logical to "change the [LIBOR=C2=A0submission] rates . . . so that=
 they lined up with what the brokers were predicting" because "the brokers =
have access to all the banks, they know where we can borrow money or they t=
hink they know where we can borrow money." But King said that while sometim=
es the rates the brokers were suggesting were all similar, "there [we]re pe=
riods when the rates are vastly different"; and then "[we] have to come up =
with something that we feel is a fair reflection of our rate." Thus, in sub=
mitting LIBOR rates, "some days [King] went with the pricer, some days [he]=
