h of those two prices should be submitted.=C2=A0So in theory on any particu=
lar day there could have been a wide range of answers to the question =E2=
=80=9Cwhat is the rate at which you could borrow funds in reasonable size,=
=E2=80=9D and if the submitter pushed his number up or down by a few basis =
points to favor a derivatives trader=E2=80=99s positions, he might still en=
d up with a number in that range =E2=80=94=C2=A0a number that was=C2=A0a fa=
ctually correct answer to the question.[7]What a great opinion. Intuitively=
 this makes a lot=C2=A0of sense. Libor asked banks to make up a number. The=
 banks made up numbers. Prosecutors decided in hindsight that some of these=
 made-up numbers were =E2=80=9Ctrue=E2=80=9D and fulfilled the abstract pur=
pose of Libor, while others were =E2=80=9Cfalse=E2=80=9D and constituted cr=
iminal fraud for which=C2=A0people should go to prison.[8] But all the numb=
ers were made up! They were all guesses, and the distinction between guesse=
