 =20
Investment banking is a bit of an unusual job in that it recruits a lot of =
smart ambitious impressive people who have great career options and really =
don't like investment banking. There is just widespread acceptance that peo=
ple who did well at certain universities but don't really know what to do w=
ith themselves will spend some time as investment-banking analysts, and som=
e of them will love it and make a career of investment banking, and others =
will use the training and connections from their analyst program to pursue =
a career in the broader financial or corporate worlds, and some of them wil=
l hate it and write essays about how they should have been sex workers inst=
ead. Here is Wade Osei Pryor in the Root:I quickly realized I had no intere=
st in watching stock markets or obsessing over company performance metrics,=
 but I=E2=80=99d never heard of anyone walking away from Goldman. Two summe=
r internships, one college graduation, and six months of full-time work lat=
er, and I=E2=80=99ve still never chosen to start my day with the=C2=A0Wall =
Street Journal. Above all, I struggle with my own complicity in perpetuatin=
g the inequalities of global capitalism. The simplest and most compelling r=
eason I have for not wanting to work at Goldman Sachs, however, is that I f=
eel no sense of passion for finance, which is why, as I write this, I consi=
dered a markedly different kind of employment offer. It came in the form of=
 a message from a 50-something on Grindr whom I=E2=80=99ve never met: =E2=
=80=9CHi Wade. Ken here =E2=80=94 great pic. I=E2=80=99m looking for a boyf=
riend to spoil with a weekly allowance=E2=80=A6Let me know if you=E2=80=99r=
e interested xx.=E2=80=9DKen was but the latest in a seemingly endless stri=
ng of older men to contact me in hopes of exchanging money for romantic att=
ention. While I=E2=80=99ve never engaged in sex work, I don=E2=80=99t imagi=
ne it being too huge a departure from working in finance =E2=80=94 both wou=
ld demand the shelving of my genuine passions in order to exchange large am=
ounts of emotional, mental, and physical labor for capital. ...I began to w=
onder why wouldn=E2=80=99t I consider Ken=E2=80=99s offer? From a purely ec=
onomic point of view, turning him down would be illogical: Goldman demands =
far more of my time and energy than I imagine Ken would (for context, I wor=
ked over 110 hours the week he messaged me), yet in return they offer only =
fractions of his proposed weekly allowance. Goldman may provide opportuniti=
es for career advancement that being a sugar baby likely wouldn=E2=80=99t, =
but I might be able to mitigate that concern by taking on multiple Kens and=
 saving for the future. If I=E2=80=99m going to exploit myself for capital,=
 then why wouldn=E2=80=99t I do so in a way that maximizes my return and is=
 least in conflict with my values? ...I know I=E2=80=99m fortunate to have =
the option of choosing a profession based solely on how passionate I am abo=
ut the work, and it would be foolish to let money or status or external val=
idation prevent me taking advantage of that. After my brief six-month stint=
 in finance, I now spend my days as an architecture apprentice at a family-=
run studio in Genoa, working under two architects I really admire.=C2=A0He =
probably could have just gone directly into architecture? But he graduated =
from Harvard =E2=80=9Chaving not yet identified my own calling=E2=80=9D so =
he went to Goldman instead. And, like so many Goldman analysts, he stayed u=
p all night building spreadsheets and wishing he was doing something else.I=
 have to say that this essay made me sort of bullish on Goldman Sachs Group=
 Inc.? (Disclosure, I also once worked there.) I suspect that the main thin=
g that Goldman wants out of its college recruiting is to be the destination=
 of choice for smart talented ambitious confident well-connected interestin=
g young people who don=E2=80=99t really know what to do with themselves. If=
 you get enough of those people, you will be able to turn a few of them (al=
l you need!) into good bankers and traders, and you will turn a lot more of=
 them into good private-equity and hedge-fund investors or corporate execut=
ives who will think fondly of Goldman and be lucrative clients, all of whic=
h is good. But also some of them will end up leaving the industry entirely =
and becoming=C2=A0interesting and sort of decorative; some pop star or foot=
ball player or distinguished architect or renowned=C2=A0sugar baby or maste=
r criminal or newsletter writer will pop up in the news and you=E2=80=99ll =
be able to say =E2=80=9Coh I knew him when he was at Goldman.=E2=80=9D That=
 might be good for business, it=E2=80=99s certainly good for recruiting (=
=E2=80=9Ctwo years at Goldman will actually=C2=A0help=C2=A0you become a pop=
 star,=E2=80=9D you tell some kid who=E2=80=99s on the fence), but mostly i=
t is good for your self-esteem. =E2=80=9CI don't just work at a job that pa=
ys well,=E2=80=9D you can tell yourself; =E2=80=9CI work at a great general=
-purpose incubator of talent.=E2=80=9D The interestingness of the alumni po=
ol rubs off on the people who stay.I have in the past  suggested that Goldm=
an might be losing that status as a generic elite finishing school, that po=
st-crisis regulations and the fall in prestige=C2=A0of banking and the rise=
 of big tech firms has cut into Goldman=E2=80=99s allure. But here=E2=80=99=
s this guy!=C2=A0The system still works!
