r great Bloomberg newsletters here. Thanks![1] A minor part of the post-sca=
ndal Libor cleanup is that Libor is now run by=C2=A0ICE Benchmark Administr=
ation Ltd.[2] Actually there are other poll-based indexes, though usually w=
ith less riding on them than Libor. One that we have discussed a lot is the=
 Georgia Dock index of poultry prices, or =E2=80=9CChicken Libor,=E2=80=9D =
which  had its own manipulation scandal.[3] It is less relevant to our purp=
oses here, but another important=C2=A0part of the Libor scandal is that, du=
ring the 2008 financial crisis, banks lied about their borrowing costs not =
(just) to manipulate derivatives but rather to avoid spooking the market. L=
ibor panel submissions were public, and if three-month dollar Libor was 3.0=
0% one day, and the next day the BBA called one big bank and said =E2=80=9C=
what would you pay to borrow dollars for three months,=E2=80=9D and the ban=
k said =E2=80=9Cuh, 7%,=E2=80=9D then everyone would know that that bank wa=
s in distress and having trouble funding itself, and that would lead to a r=
un on the bank. So at the worst points of the crisis banks understated thei=
r borrowing rates, leading Libor to be systematically depressed for a while=
. This was less of a focus of enforcement actions than the derivatives-mani=
pulation stuff, because (1) it is less obviously evil and greedy and (2) ce=
ntral bankers and regulators seem to have =E2=80=A6=C2=A0known about and en=
couraged it? =E2=80=9CNot sparking panic in the bank funding markets=E2=80=
=9D is an important goal of banks, but also of bank regulators, and lying a=
 bit about Libor was for a while an acceptable cost for both of them.[4] Mo=
st notably Tom Hayes, who traded interest rate derivatives for UBS Group AG=
 and Citigroup Inc., manipulated Libor,=C2=A0was prosecuted in the U.K. and=
 spent about  six years in prison.[5] The case here involved convictions fo=
r wire fraud under 18 U.S.C. 1343, which involves =E2=80=9Cany scheme or ar=
tifice to defraud, or for obtaining money or property by means of false or =
fraudulent pretenses, representations, or promises.=E2=80=9D It is not tota=
lly clear that those words require actual lying, which the court discusses =
on pages 30 to 32 of last week=E2=80=99s opinion.[6] The BBA question is qu=
oted on page 9 of last week=E2=80=99s Second Circuit opinion.[7]=C2=A0In fa=
ct the Libor instructions didn=E2=80=99t even tell banks not to consider th=
eir derivatives positions: =E2=80=9CAlthough the government states that the=
 BBA's =E2=80=98instructions did not allow a panel bank, when submitting it=
s honest estimate of its borrowing costs, to consider the submission's effe=
ct on the profitability of interest rate swaps or other derivatives positio=
ns held by the bank's traders,=E2=80=99 in fact the BBA LIBOR Instruction c=
ontained no such prohibition.=C2=A0In contrast, the BBA did evince a concer=
n about collusion between panel banks. The BBA LIBOR Instruction expressly =
stated that =E2=80=98Contributor Banks shall input their rate without refer=
ence to rates contributed by other Contributor=C2=A0Banks.=E2=80=99=C2=A0Bu=
t there was no similar prohibition against banks' making their LIBOR submis=
sions with consideration of the=C2=A0bank's own interest-rate-sensitive der=
ivatives.=E2=80=9D I think you could make an argument that, look, some bank=
s will pay Libor in their derivatives, and others will receive Libor, and t=
hey will all have incentives to tweak the rates, and those incentives will =
roughly balance out and the resulting Libor =E2=80=94=C2=A0influenced by de=
rivatives positions =E2=80=94=C2=A0will reflect something real and market-d=
riven, though that real market-driven thing might not literally be banks=E2=
=80=99 unsecured funding costs.=C2=A0[8] Black and Connolly were actually s=
entenced to probation, fines and home confinement, and the government appea=
led their sentences to try to send them to prison.
