<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Liebor</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way that global financial markets =
worked for decades is that trillions of dollars of floating-rate loans and =
interest-rate derivatives were indexed to Libor, the London interbank offer=
ed rate. And the way Libor worked was that someone =E2=80=94=C2=A0at the ti=
me relevant to our story=C2=A0it was the British Bankers=E2=80=99 Associati=
on[1] =E2=80=94=C2=A0would call up a group of big international banks and a=
sk them =E2=80=9Chow much would you have to pay right now to borrow dollars=
 for one month,=E2=80=9D and they=E2=80=99d answer, and the BBA would take =
some trimmed average of their answers, and that was one-month dollar Libor.=
 And there were other Libors for other currencies and tenors, computed in t=
he same way.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Most important financial bench=
marks do not work this way. The S&amp;P 500 index is not calculated by call=
ing some banks and saying =E2=80=9Chey how=C2=A0much would you pay for thes=
e 500 stocks=E2=80=9D and averaging their answers. The S&amp;P 500 index is=
 calculated based on the last trade of each stock on a public stock exchang=
e. Most indexes are based on actual trades.[2] But Libor was invented becau=
se it was <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26548191=
.257626/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDQ=
tMTEvYmFua3Mtd2lsbC1taXNzLWxpYm9yLXdoZW4taXQtcy1nb25lP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMzEyMl=
9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90Z=
XJtPTIyMDEzMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcb33=
a5e1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;"> very useful</a>, for the floating-rate loan business, to hav=
e an index of=C2=A0<em>banks=E2=80=99 unsecured borrowing costs</em>, and u=
nsecured short-term bank debt did not really trade on a transparent public =
exchange. It traded=C2=A0in an informal, telephone-based interbank market, =
and the easiest way to find out what trades banks were doing was to call th=
em.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, though, they didn=E2=80=99t do tr=
ades in every Libor tenor and currency every day. If you wanted to know how=
 much a bank would pay to borrow Danish kroner for two months =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0which was <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26548=
191.257626/aHR0cHM6Ly9mcmVkLnN0bG91aXNmZWQub3JnL3Nlcmllcy9ES0syTVREMTU2Tg/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB72473f8d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a real Libor rate</a> =E2=80=94 y=
ou could not compute that every day based on how much each Libor bank actua=
lly paid to borrow kroner for two months that day. Big international banks =
did not borrow kroner for two months every day.=C2=A0Certainly not every da=
y at exactly the time the BBA called them to ask. But a bank which had borr=
owed kroner for one month an hour ago, and borrowed dollars for three month=
s five minutes ago, and had a general sense of the curve of its various sho=
rt-term borrowing costs, could probably give you a good guess at how much i=
t would have to pay to borrow kroner for two months right now. So you could=
 just call it and ask it for that guess. Libor was =E2=80=9Cthe rate at whi=
ch banks don't lend to each other,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/26548191.257626/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGVsZWdyYXBoLmNvL=
nVrL2ZpbmFuY2UvZWNvbm9taWNzLzI3OTU5NjIvRm9ybWVyLU1QQy1tYW4tY2FsbHMtZm9yLUxp=
Ym9yLXRvLWJlLXJlcGxhY2VkLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbf4d16f0" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
people said</a>.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The problem is that Libor =
also became the rate underpinning trillions of dollars of derivatives contr=
acts, and the banks traded those derivatives and built up large positions. =
And some days it would be good for the derivatives traders to have a low Li=
bor =E2=80=94=C2=A0they had to pay Libor on a bunch of contracts resetting =
that day, so a low Libor would let them pay less =E2=80=94=C2=A0and other d=
ays it would be good for the derivatives traders to have a high Libor. And =
the derivatives traders realized that, if it was worth $1,000,000 to their =
bank to have Libor be one basis point lower, then it was worth $200,000 to =
their bonus to have Libor be one basis point lower, which meant that it was=
 worth calling up their bank=E2=80=99s Libor submitter =E2=80=94=C2=A0the p=
erson who answered the phone when the BBA called =E2=80=94=C2=A0and saying =
=E2=80=9Chey mate I=E2=80=99ll buy you a case of Champagne if you submit a =
lower Libor.=E2=80=9D And then the BBA would call the submitter and say =E2=
=80=9Cwhere can you borrow yen for three months,=E2=80=9D and the submitter=
 would say =E2=80=9Coh 0.525=E2=80=9D when in his heart of hearts he knew=
=C2=A0that the real answer was 0.545, and the BBA would average that in, an=
d 3-month yen Libor would be a smidge=C2=A0lower than it would otherwise ha=
ve been, and the bank would make money on the derivatives, and the derivati=
ves traders would get their bonuses and the submitter would get <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26548191.257626/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cucmV1dGVycy5jb20vYXJ0aWNsZS91cy1iYXJjbGF5cy1saWJvci1lbWFpbHMvZG9uZS1mb3It=
eW91LWJpZy1ib3ktaG93LWVtYWlscy1uYWlsZWQtYmFyY2xheXMtaWRVU0JSRTg1UTFKWTIwMTI=
wNjI3/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB52f2e8b9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">his Champagne</a>.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This went on for a while and eventually regulato=
rs and prosecutors noticed it and it became a huge huge huge scandal[3] and=
:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16p=
x 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Banks were fined <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26548191.257626/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud=
GhlZ3VhcmRpYW4uY29tL2J1c2luZXNzLzIwMTUvYXByLzIzL2xpYm9yLXJpZ2dpbmctZmluZXMt=
YS10aW1lbGluZQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBad84529a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> billions</a> and=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26548191.257626/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2ZyLm9yZy9iYWNrZ3JvdW5kZXIvdW5kZXJzdGFuZGluZy1saWJvci1zY2Fu=
ZGFsIzp-OnRleHQ9UmVndWxhdG9ycyUyMGluJTIwdGhlJTIwVW5pdGVkJTIwU3RhdGVzLHRyaWx=
saW9uJTIwd29ydGglMjBvZiUyMGxvYW5zJTIwd29ybGR3aWRlLg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB701c1764" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> billions</a> of dollars for rigging Libor;</li>=09<li =
