range =E2=80=94=C2=A0a number that was=C2=A0a factually correct answer to t=
he question.[7]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What a great opinion. Intui=
tively this makes a lot=C2=A0of sense. Libor asked banks to make up a numbe=
r. The banks made up numbers. Prosecutors decided in hindsight that some of=
 these made-up numbers were =E2=80=9Ctrue=E2=80=9D and fulfilled the abstra=
ct purpose of Libor, while others were =E2=80=9Cfalse=E2=80=9D and constitu=
ted criminal fraud for which=C2=A0people should go to prison.[8] But all th=
e numbers were made up! They were all guesses, and the distinction between =
guesses that were good and guesses that were crimes had nothing to do with =
their correspondence to objective truth; it was just about which guesses ca=
me with embarrassing chats and impure motives.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">In other ways it is a strange result. Libor is=C2=A0<em>impossible to m=
anipulate</em>, the opinion suggests, or rather impossible to manipulate cr=
iminally. Because it was made up, you could make up anything with any sort =
of nefarious purpose and=C2=A0that would be fine. From <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26548191.257626/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLm=
NvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9hbGwtdS1zLXRyaWFsLWNvbnZpY3Rpb25zLWluLWNyaXNpcy1lcmEtbGlib=
3ItcmlnZ2luZy1oYXZlLW5vdy1iZWVuLW92ZXJ0dXJuZWQtMTE2NDMzMTAxNzg_bW9kPWl0cF93=
c2omcnU9eWFob28/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb9f3e0d2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the Wall Street =
Journal</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIn some w=
ays, these reversals underscore what a screwed-up benchmark Libor was to be=
gin with, when you are not being asked to submit actual offers or bids, but=
 just hypotheticals,=E2=80=9D said Aitan Goelman, a former director of enfo=
rcement for the Commodity Futures Trading Commission, a civil regulator tha=
t fined many banks for Libor violations. =E2=80=9CIt almost begged to be ma=
nipulated.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But what i=
s most interesting to me is not that it might be impossible ever to prove t=
hat a bank made a false=C2=A0Libor submission on any given day, but that th=
e prosecutors=C2=A0<em>didn=E2=80=99t try</em>. You can sort of understand =
where they were coming from. This=C2=A0<em>looked=C2=A0</em>bad. The banks =
paid billions of dollars in fines for it. If you stand up in front of a jur=
y of normal people and said =E2=80=9Cthese bank traders made a number highe=
r so that they could make more money=E2=80=9D the jury will jump up and sho=
ut =E2=80=9Cguilty=E2=80=9D before you can finish the sentence. There is a =
popular=C2=A0narrative of corrupt bankers secretly conspiring to make money=
 by nefarious means, and this story fits that narrative so completely that =
the prosecutors didn=E2=80=99t even think they had to prove that the banker=
s were lying!</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content" width=3D"aut=
