<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Goldman vs. sugar babying</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investment banking is a bit of an unus=
ual job in that it recruits a lot of smart ambitious impressive people who =
have great career options and <em>really don't like investment banking</em>=
. There is just widespread acceptance that people who did well at certain u=
niversities but don't really know what to do with themselves will spend som=
e time as investment-banking analysts, and some of them will love it and ma=
ke a career of investment banking, and others will use the training and con=
nections from their analyst program to pursue a career in the broader finan=
cial or corporate worlds, and some of them will hate it and write essays ab=
out how they should have been sex workers instead. Here is <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26548191.257626/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudG=
hlcm9vdC5jb20vbXktdHdvLWpvYi1vZmZlcnMtZ29sZG1hbi1zYWNocy12cy1ncmluZHItMTg0O=
DQxNjUyOQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0c0b3212" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Wade Osei Pryor in the=
 Root</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I quickly realized I=
 had no interest in watching stock markets or obsessing over company perfor=
mance metrics, but I=E2=80=99d never heard of anyone walking away from Gold=
man. Two summer internships, one college graduation, and six months of full=
-time work later, and I=E2=80=99ve still never chosen to start my day with =
the=C2=A0<em>Wall Street Journal</em>. Above all, I struggle with my own co=
mplicity in perpetuating the inequalities of global capitalism. The simples=
t and most compelling reason I have for not wanting to work at Goldman Sach=
s, however, is that I feel no sense of passion for finance, which is why, a=
s I write this, I considered a markedly different kind of employment offer.=
 It came in the form of a message from a 50-something on Grindr whom I=E2=
=80=99ve never met: =E2=80=9CHi Wade. Ken here =E2=80=94 great pic. I=E2=80=
=99m looking for a boyfriend to spoil with a weekly allowance=E2=80=A6Let m=
e know if you=E2=80=99re interested xx.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">Ken was but the latest in a seemingly endless string of older men to =
contact me in hopes of exchanging money for romantic attention. While I=E2=
=80=99ve never engaged in sex work, I don=E2=80=99t imagine it being too hu=
ge a departure from working in finance =E2=80=94 both would demand the shel=
ving of my genuine passions in order to exchange large amounts of emotional=
, mental, and physical labor for capital. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">I began to wonder why wouldn=E2=80=99t I consider Ken=E2=80=99s offer? F=
rom a purely economic point of view, turning him down would be illogical: G=
oldman demands far more of my time and energy than I imagine Ken would (for=
 context, I worked over 110 hours the week he messaged me), yet in return t=
hey offer only fractions of his proposed weekly allowance. Goldman may prov=
ide opportunities for career advancement that being a sugar baby likely wou=
ldn=E2=80=99t, but I might be able to mitigate that concern by taking on mu=
ltiple Kens and saving for the future. If I=E2=80=99m going to exploit myse=
lf for capital, then why wouldn=E2=80=99t I do so in a way that maximizes m=
y return and is least in conflict with my values? ...</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">I know I=E2=80=99m fortunate to have the option of choosing a pr=
ofession based solely on how passionate I am about the work, and it would b=
e foolish to let money or status or external validation prevent me taking a=
dvantage of that. After my brief six-month stint in finance, I now spend my=
 days as an architecture apprentice at a family-run studio in Genoa, workin=
